money not tax funded monies. Should a student receive a &quot;D&quot; the parents of the homeschooled children would receive a one time warning to either re-teach and re-test the material or send the student to public school for professional teaching. I'm all for religious freedom but there are cases when the religious freedom of the parent is not in the best interest of the child. That could be from not having health care treatments for a child (I.E. cancer) to not teaching core curriculum the student would need to function in modern society. There can be a fine line between religious belief and religious abuse. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="918" language="en" documentId="116" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Shingo56" date="7/29/2013 11:45 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375134351-441-336" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="116" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="918"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>